            <section id="introduction">
                <h2>1. Introduction</h2>
                <p>Semantic HTML is the practice of using HTML tags that accurately describe the content they contain. This approach goes beyond just visual presentation, giving deeper meaning to your web page's structure. In this post, we'll explore why it's so important.</p>
            </section>
            
            <section id="main-content">
                <h2>2. The Core Benefits</h2>
                <p>When you write semantic code, you're not just telling the browser how to display text; you're providing context. For instance, using `<strong>` tells the browser that the text has strong importance, not just that it should be bold.</p>
                
                <figure>
                    <img src="https://placehold.co/600x300/222/FFF?text=Semantic+HTML+Code" alt="A placeholder image showing an example of semantic HTML code">
                    <figcaption>Fig 1: Semantic tags provide structure and meaning.</figcaption>
                </figure>

                <p>Key benefits include:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Improved Accessibility:</strong> Screen readers can interpret the page structure more effectively, providing a better experience for visually impaired users.</li>
                    <li><strong>Better SEO:</strong> Search engines like Google can better understand and rank your content, as the structure is clear.</li>
                    <li><strong>Easier Maintenance:</strong> Your code becomes more readable and easier for you or other developers to update in the future.</li>
                </ul>

                <blockquote>
                    "Accessibility is not a feature, it's a social contract."
                    <cite>- A wise developer</cite>
                </blockquote>
            </section>

            <section id="conclusion">
                <h2>3. Conclusion</h2>
                <p>Ultimately, embracing semantic HTML isn't just about following rules; it's about building a better, more inclusive web üåê. By writing code that has inherent meaning, we create digital experiences that are robust, accessible to all users, and easier for fellow developers to build upon. It‚Äôs a fundamental skill that elevates your work from merely functional to truly professional.</p>
            </section>

